HOUSE BILL 1117 5
1 1. A DEVICE DESCRIBED IN SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS
2 PARAGRAPH THAT HAS FEATURES THAT ENABLE THE SECURE STORAGE AND
3 TRANSMISSION OF CRITICAL INDIVIDUAL INFORMATION TO CAREGIVERS,
4 EMERGENCY PERSONNEL, OR FIRST RESPONDERS TO FACILITATE TIMELY,
5 INFORMED, AND COORDINATED RESPONSE IN ELOPEMENT EMERGENCY
6 SITUATIONS; AND
7 2. ANY ELECTRONIC MONITORING SERVICES
8 NECESSARY FOR A DEVICE DESCRIBED IN SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH
9 TO FUNCTION AS A MEDICAL SAFETY AND ASSISTIVE TOOL.
10 (B) THE ADVISORY STAKEHOLDER GROUP ON AUTISM–RELATED NEEDS
11 MAY RECOMMEND THE USE OF ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES AS SAFETY TOOLS
12 FOR INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE AT RISK OF ELOPEMENT BECAUSE OF AUTISM.
13 SUBTITLE 32B. ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES.
14 13–32B–01.
15 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
16 INDICATED.
17 (B) “APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE” HAS THE MEANING
18 STATED IN § 15–160 OF THIS ARTICLE.
19 (C) “ELOPEMENT” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 15–160 OF THIS
20 ARTICLE.
21 13–32B–02.
22 (A) THIS SECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO THE MARYLAND MEDICAL
23 ASSISTANCE PROGRAM.
24 (B) (1) EXCEPT AS OTHERWISE PROVIDED BY LAW, IF A STATE PROGRAM
25 PROVIDES FUNDING OR REIMBURSEMENT FOR OR THE DIRECT PROVISION OF
26 MEDICAL EQUIPMENT OR MEDICAL–RELATED SUPPLIES TO OLDER ADULTS OR
27 INDIVIDUALS WITH DISABILITIES, THE STATE PROGRAM SHALL CONSIDER AN
28 APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE TO BE A MEDICAL DEVICE, DURABLE
29 MEDICAL EQUIPMENT, OR ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY FOR PURPOSES OF THE STATE
30 PROGRAM.
31 (2) PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION APPLIES WITHOUT REGARD
32 TO WHEN THE STATE PROGRAM WAS ESTABLISHED.

6 HOUSE BILL 1117
1 15–103.
2 (a) (1) The Secretary shall administer the Maryland Medical Assistance
3 Program.
4 (2) The Program:
5 (xxvii) Beginning on January 1, 2026, if providing coverage for the
6 delivery of anesthesia, shall provide coverage for the delivery of anesthesia in accordance
7 with § 15–862 of the Insurance Article; [and]
8 (xxviii) Beginning on January 1, 2026, shall provide calcium score
9 testing in accordance with § 15–863 of the Insurance Article; AND
10 (XXIX) SHALL PROVIDE, SUBJECT TO THE LIMITATIONS OF
11 THE STATE BUDGET AND FEDERAL FINANCIAL PARTICIPATION, COVERAGE OF
12 ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES AND SUPPORTS IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 15–160 OF
13 THIS SUBTITLE.
14 15–160.
15 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
16 INDICATED.
17 (2) (I) “APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE” MEANS A
18 MEDICAL DEVICE OR ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY APPROVED BY THE DEPARTMENT FOR
19 THE PREVENTION OF OR RESPONSE TO ELOPEMENT.
20 (II) “APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE” INCLUDES
21 DOOR OR WINDOW SENSORS, WEARABLE OR PORTABLE LOCATION–ENABLED
22 DEVICES, AND RELATED ALERTING TECHNOLOGY.
23 (3) “ELIGIBLE RECIPIENT” MEANS A PROGRAM RECIPIENT WHO:
24 (I) IS UNDER THE AGE OF 21 YEARS AND ELIGIBLE FOR EARLY
25 AND PERIODIC SCREENING, DIAGNOSTIC, AND TREATMENT SERVICES, AS DEFINED
26 IN § 15–149 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
27 (II) IS ELIGIBLE FOR COVERAGE THROUGH A HOME– AND
28 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES WAIVER; OR
29 (III) HAS BEEN DIAGNOSED WITH ALZHEIMER’S DISEASE OR A
30 RELATED DEMENTIA AND MEETS MEDICAL NECESSITY CRITERIA ESTABLISHED BY
31 THE DEPARTMENT.

HOUSE BILL 1117 7
1 (4) (I) “ELOPEMENT” MEANS BEHAVIOR IN WHICH AN INDIVIDUAL
2 WITH A COGNITIVE, DEVELOPMENTAL, OR NEUROLOGICAL CONDITION LEAVES OR
3 ATTEMPTS TO LEAVE A SAFE AND SUPERVISED AREA WITHOUT:
4 1. THE ABILITY TO RECOGNIZE OR AVOID RISK; OR
5 2. THE ABILITY TO RETURN SAFELY WITHOUT
6 ASSISTANCE.
7 (II) “ELOPEMENT” INCLUDES WANDERING THAT CREATES A
8 RISK OF HARM, INJURY, OR DEATH.
9 (5) “QUALIFIED LICENSED PROVIDER” MEANS A PHYSICIAN, A NURSE
10 PRACTITIONER, A PHYSICIAN’S ASSISTANT, OR ANY OTHER LICENSED HEALTH CARE
11 PRACTITIONER ACTING WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THE HEALTH CARE PRACTITIONER’S
12 LICENSE.
13 (6) “QUALIFYING PLAN” MEANS AN INDIVIDUALIZED EDUCATION
14 PROGRAM, A BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PLAN, AN INDIVIDUALIZED FAMILY SERVICE
15 PLAN, OR ANY OTHER CLINICAL OR EDUCATIONAL PLAN THAT DOCUMENTS A
16 HISTORY OR RISK OF ELOPEMENT.
17 (B) (1) SUBJECT TO FEDERAL APPROVAL, THE PROGRAM SHALL COVER
18 AN APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE AND ASSOCIATED SUPPORTS FOR AN
19 ELIGIBLE RECIPIENT WHEN ORDERED OR PRESCRIBED BY A QUALIFIED LICENSED
20 PROVIDER AND DOCUMENTED IN A QUALIFYING PLAN.
21 (2) COVERAGE MAY BE PROVIDED UNDER THE STATE PLAN,
22 INCLUDING:
23 (I) AS DURABLE MEDICAL EQUIPMENT OR A COMPARABLE
24 BENEFIT CATEGORY;
25 (II) AS AN EPSDT SERVICE WHEN MEDICALLY NECESSARY FOR
26 ELIGIBLE RECIPIENTS UNDER THE AGE OF 21 YEARS; OR
27 (III) AS ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY OR SPECIALIZED MEDICAL
28 EQUIPMENT FOR PURPOSES OF A HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES
29 WAIVER.
30 (3) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ESTABLISH:

8 HOUSE BILL 1117
1 (I) REASONABLE PRIOR AUTHORIZATION TO ENSURE
2 COST–EFFECTIVENESS OF APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES PROVIDED
3 UNDER THE PROGRAM; AND
4 (II) REPLACEMENT AND MAINTENANCE REQUIREMENTS FOR
5 APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES PROVIDED UNDER THE PROGRAM TO
6 ENSURE SAFETY OF ELIGIBLE RECIPIENTS.
7 (C) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL REQUIRE INFORMED CONSENT FOR
8 ANY LOCATION–ENABLED DEVICE FROM THE ELIGIBLE RECIPIENT OR, IF THE
9 ELIGIBLE RECIPIENT LACKS THE CAPACITY TO CONSENT, THE ENROLLEE’S PARENT
10 OR GUARDIAN.
11 (2) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT PRIVACY SAFEGUARDS AND
12 DATA MINIMIZATION STANDARDS FOR APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES,
13 INCLUDING LIMITS ON DATA ELEMENTS, RETENTION, AND ACCESS CONSISTENT
14 WITH FEDERAL AND STATE LAW.
15 (3) THE USE OF AN APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE OR
16 FAILURE TO USE AN APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE UNDER THIS
17 SECTION MAY NOT BE A CONDITION OF ELIGIBILITY FOR SERVICES OR BENEFITS
18 UNDER THE PROGRAM.
19 (D) AN APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE MAY NOT BE
20 DETERMINED TO BE INELIGIBLE FOR COVERAGE OR FUNDING UNDER THIS SECTION
21 OR ANY OTHER STATE PROGRAM SOLELY ON THE BASIS THAT THE APPROVED
22 DEVICE INCORPORATES GLOBAL POSITIONING SYSTEM TECHNOLOGY, WIRELESS
23 COMMUNICATIONS, OR CONSUMER–AVAILABLE COMPONENTS.
24 (E) THE DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT
25 OF EDUCATION, SHALL ISSUE GUIDANCE TO ENABLE SCHOOL–BASED BILLING OR
26 COST ALLOCATION WHEN FEDERALLY ALLOWABLE, INCLUDING FOR USE OF
27 APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICES IN SCHOOL SETTINGS CONSISTENT
28 WITH A QUALIFYING PLAN.
29 (F) (1) ON OR BEFORE OCTOBER 1, 2026, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
30 SUBMIT ANY NECESSARY STATE PLAN AMENDMENTS AND, IF APPLICABLE, WAIVER
31 AMENDMENTS TO CARRY OUT THIS SECTION.
32 (2) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL MAXIMIZE FEDERAL FINANCIAL
33 PARTICIPATION.

HOUSE BILL 1117 9
1 (3) THE DEPARTMENT MAY ESTABLISH PILOTS OR PHASED
2 IMPLEMENTATION.
3 (G) THE DEPARTMENT MAY CARRY OUT THIS SECTION THROUGH
4 REGULATIONS, PROVIDER BULLETINS, OR GUIDANCE PRIOR TO FINAL ADOPTION OF
5 REGULATIONS.
6 (H) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2027, AND EACH DECEMBER 1
7 THEREAFTER THROUGH 2029, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL REPORT TO THE SENATE
8 FINANCE COMMITTEE AND THE HOUSE HEALTH COMMITTEE, IN ACCORDANCE
9 WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, ON IMPLEMENTATION
10 STATUS, UTILIZATION OF APPROVED DEVICES, COSTS, AND OUTCOMES.
11 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
12 as follows:
13 Article – Insurance
14 15–801.
15 (a) This section applies to:
16 (1) insurers that propose to issue or deliver in the State group or blanket
17 health insurance policies that are written on an expense–incurred basis; and
18 (2) nonprofit health service plans that propose to issue or deliver in the
19 State group medical or major medical contracts that are written on an expense–incurred
20 basis.
21 (b) [An] SUBJECT TO § 15–801.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE, AN entity subject to this
22 section shall offer the policyholder the option of providing benefits for expenses arising from
23 the care, including nursing home care and intermediate or custodial nursing care, of
24 individuals who have Alzheimer’s disease.
25 (c) [An] SUBJECT TO § 15–801.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE, AN entity subject to this
26 section shall offer the policyholder the option of providing benefits for expenses arising from
27 the care of elderly individuals, including nursing home care and intermediate or custodial
28 nursing care of elderly individuals who have any disease, other than Alzheimer’s disease,
29 that is designated in regulations adopted by the Commissioner.
30 (d) An entity subject to this section may establish reasonable limits on the
31 benefits offered under this section, including copayment and deductible provisions and
32 maximum annual and lifetime dollar limits.
33 15–801.1.

10 HOUSE BILL 1117
1 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
2 INDICATED.
3 (2) “APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE” HAS THE MEANING
4 STATED IN § 15–160 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
5 (3) “ELIGIBLE INDIVIDUAL” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO HAS BEEN
6 DIAGNOSED WITH ALZHEIMER’S DISEASE OR A RELATED DEMENTIA AND MEETS
7 MEDICAL NECESSITY CRITERIA ESTABLISHED BY THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF
8 HEALTH.
9 (4) “ELOPEMENT” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 15–160 OF THE
10 HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
11 (5) “QUALIFIED LICENSED PROVIDER” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN
12 § 15–160 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
13 (6) “QUALIFYING PLAN” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 15–160 OF
14 THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
15 (B) THIS SECTION APPLIES TO:
16 (1) INSURERS AND NONPROFIT HEALTH SERVICE PLANS THAT
17 PROVIDE HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, OR SURGICAL BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS
18 ON AN EXPENSE–INCURRED BASIS UNDER HEALTH INSURANCE POLICIES OR
19 CONTRACTS THAT ARE ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE; AND
20 (2) HEALTH MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE
21 HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, OR SURGICAL BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS UNDER
22 CONTRACTS THAT ARE ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE.
23 (C) AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE COVERAGE FOR
24 AN APPROVED ELOPEMENT RESPONSE DEVICE AND ASSOCIATED SUPPORTS FOR AN
25 ELIGIBLE INDIVIDUAL WHEN ORDERED OR PRESCRIBED BY A QUALIFIED LICENSED
26 PROVIDER AND DOCUMENTED IN A QUALIFYING PLAN.
27 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Section 2 of this Act shall
28 apply to all policies, contracts, and health benefit plans issued, delivered, or renewed in the
29 State on or after January 1, 2027.
30 SECTION 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Section 2 of this Act shall take
31 effect January 1, 2027.

HOUSE BILL 1117 11
1 SECTION 5. 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, except as provided in
2 Section 4 of this Act, this Act shall take effect July 1, 2026.
